Here's what needs to change for each item when moving to .NET 10:

---

### 1. `WebHostBuilder` → `WebApplication.CreateBuilder()`

The legacy `WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder()` hosting model is removed in .NET 10. Migrate to the minimal hosting model:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
var host = WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)
    .UseStartup<Startup>()
    .Build();
host.Run();

// After (.NET 10)
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
// Move Startup.ConfigureServices() logic here
var app = builder.Build();
// Move Startup.Configure() logic here
app.Run();
```

Collapse your `Startup` class into `Program.cs` (or extract helpers). `IWebHostBuilder` and `IStartup` are gone.

---

### 2. `.WithOpenApi()` removed

The `WithOpenApi()` endpoint extension is removed. Use the built-in OpenAPI document generation instead:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
app.MapGet("/items", () => ...)
   .WithOpenApi();

// After (.NET 10)
builder.Services.AddOpenApi();   // in service config
app.MapOpenApi();                // in pipeline — serves /openapi/v1.json

app.MapGet("/items", () => ...); // endpoints are included automatically
```

Use `[EndpointDescription]`, `[EndpointSummary]`, and `Produces<T>()` to enrich metadata — no per-endpoint opt-in needed.

---

### 3. `<IncludeOpenApiAnalyzers>` removed

This MSBuild property no longer exists. Remove it from your `.csproj`:

```xml
<!-- Delete this line -->
<IncludeOpenApiAnalyzers>true</IncludeOpenApiAnalyzers>
```

The new `AddOpenApi()` pipeline and standard ASP.NET Core analyzers replace it.

---

### 4. `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Client` (NSwag code-gen)

Build-time OpenAPI document generation via `dotnet-getdocument` no longer works with the minimal hosting model's `AddOpenApi()`. Two options:

- **Option A** — Generate at build time with the new `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Server` + `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Client` pipeline that targets the `/openapi/v1.json` endpoint (requires the app to be running or use the new MSBuild `OpenApiGenerateDocumentsOnBuild` property).
- **Option B** — Switch to the `Microsoft.dotnet-openapi` CLI or use `NSwag.MSBuild` pointing at the runtime-served document URL.

Review your NSwag config and update the document source accordingly.

---

### 5. `IActionContextAccessor` — no longer valid as singleton

Singleton registration now throws at runtime. Register as **scoped** (or **transient**):

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>();

// After (.NET 10)
builder.Services.AddHttpContextAccessor();              // if you only need HttpContext
builder.Services.AddScoped<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>(); // if you truly need it
```

In most cases you can replace `IActionContextAccessor` usage with `IHttpContextAccessor`, which is simpler.

---

### 6. `IPNetwork` type replaced

`Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides.IPNetwork` is removed. Use `System.Net.IPNetwork` (available since .NET 8):

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides;
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));

// After (.NET 10)
using System.Net;
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));
```

The constructor signature is the same — only the `using` and namespace change.

---

### 7. `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` removed

The `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.RuntimeCompilation` package is no longer available for .NET 10. Use **Hot Reload** instead:

```bash
dotnet watch
```

Remove the package reference and the `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` call:

```xml
<!-- Delete from .csproj -->
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.RuntimeCompilation" ... />
```

`dotnet watch` provides the same edit-and-refresh workflow for Razor files.

---

### 8. 401 → login page redirect

In .NET 10, cookie authentication defaults change for API endpoints. Instead of returning a **302 redirect** to the login page, APIs now return a proper **401** status code. If you were working around this, you can remove the workaround. If you *want* the redirect (e.g., for MVC views), configure it explicitly:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddAuthentication().AddCookie(options =>
{
    options.Events.OnRedirectToLogin = context =>
    {
        // APIs: return 401
        if (context.Request.Path.StartsWithSegments("/api"))
        {
            context.Response.StatusCode = 401;
            return Task.CompletedTask;
        }
        // MVC: keep redirect
        context.Response.Redirect(context.RedirectUri);
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    };
});
```

If your app is purely an API, the new default behavior is likely what you want — just remove any existing 401-handling workarounds.

---

### Quick checklist

| Item | Action |
|---|---|
| `WebHostBuilder` | Rewrite to `WebApplication.CreateBuilder()` |
| `.WithOpenApi()` | Delete; use `AddOpenApi()` + `MapOpenApi()` |
| `IncludeOpenApiAnalyzers` | Remove from `.csproj` |
| `ApiDescription.Client` / NSwag | Point at runtime OpenAPI endpoint |
| `IActionContextAccessor` singleton | Change to scoped (or switch to `IHttpContextAccessor`) |
| `IPNetwork` | Change `using` to `System.Net` |
| `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` | Remove; use `dotnet watch` |
| 401 redirect | Remove workarounds; new default returns 401 for APIs |
